XXXI. It is often made a question, whether this holds, if tho subjects of any sovereign do not take arms on their own account, but act in military service under others who are making war. Undoubt- edly the Cerites in Livy excuse themselves, by saying that their citizens had joined the army by no public act: and the same defense was alleged by the Rhodians. And the better opinion is, that such service is not permitted, except it appear by probable arguments that some other line was agreed on3 as we sometimes see in our days3 [that persons of another country serve in armies which are carrying on war ς] following the example of the old Etolians, who took service and gathered booty on both sides in any war, as Polybius and Livy say. In former times, the Etruscans, though they would not send aid to the Veientes, did not prevent any of their young men going as volunteers to the war.
